1) The Cartesian product of A and B, denoted as A x B, is the set of all ordered pairs (a, b) where a is in A and b is in B. So, A x B = {(2,3), (2,6), (2,9), (4,3), (4,6), (4,9), (6,3), (6,6), (6,9)}.

2) The Cartesian product of B and A, denoted as B x A, is the set of all ordered pairs (b, a) where b is in B and a is in A. So, B x A = {(3,2), (3,4), (3,6), (6,2), (6,4), (6,6), (9,2), (9,4), (9,6)}.

3) The symmetric difference between two sets is the set of elements that are in either of the sets but not in both. In this case, we are looking for the symmetric difference between A x B and B x A. 

Symmetric difference (A x B) Δ (B x A) = {(2,3), (2,6), (2,9), (4,3), (4,6), (4,9), (6,3), (6,6), (6,9), (3,2), (3,4), (3,6), (6,2), (6,4), (6,6), (9,2), (9,4), (9,6)} - {(6,6)}

So, the symmetric difference is: {(2,3), (2,6), (2,9), (4,3), (4,6), (4,9), (6,3), (6,9), (3,2), (3,4), (3,6), (6,2), (6,4), (9,2), (9,4), (9,6)}

4) Now, let's find the symmetric difference of sets A and B, denoted as A Δ B. 

A Δ B = (A - B) ∪ (B - A) = {2, 4, 9}

Now, let's find the Cartesian product of (A Δ B) x (A Δ B):

(A Δ B) x (A Δ B) = {(2,2), (2,4), (2,9), (4,2), (4,4), (4,9), (9,2), (9,4), (9,9)}

Comparing the symmetric difference obtained in (3) and the Cartesian product of (A Δ B) x (A Δ B), we can see that they are not equal:

{(2,3), (2,6), (2,9), (4,3), (4,6), (4,9), (6,3), (6,9), (3,2), (3,4), (3,6), (6,2), (6,4), (9,2), (9,4), (9,6)} ≠ {(2,2), (2,4), (2,9), (4,2), (4,4), (4,9), (9,2), (9,4), (9,9)}

Therefore, the symmetric difference obtained in (3) is not equal to the Cartesian product of (A Δ B) x (A Δ B).
